    {
      "id": "ceaad1287ad05f65a4803e4454668404256853b7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-06-06 23:57:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLiang, the patch looks good. But, it doesn't make much sense to me to have the lnet_*_free_locked() functions. E.g.:\nlnet_drop_delayed_put()\n......\n    lnet_msg_free_locked(msg);\n    LNET_UNLOCK();\n}\n\nHere it's unnecessary to hold the lock while freeing the msg. I'd rather UNLOCK() earlier:\n    LNET_UNLOCK();\n    lnet_msg_free(msg);\n}\n\nThere's quite some places like this. I don't like calling LIBCFS_FREE() with LNET_LOCK() - LIBCFS_FREE() is not cheap. I'd suggest to:\n1. Remove all lnet_*_free_locked() functions.\n2. Replace their call sites with: UNLOCK(); lnet_*_free(); In some places the changes aren't that straightforward, but I think it's worthwhile.\n3.\nlnet_xx_free()\n{\n/* Never call me with lock held */\n#if FREE_LIST_STUFF\n   lock_some();\n   free_list_free(xx);\n   unlock_some();\n#else\n   LIBCFS_FREE(xx);\n#fi\n}\n\nSo that locking is only used when LNET_USE_LIB_FREELIST defined, which is never defined for KERNEL, and for KERNEL all unnecessary LOCK are avoided.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "de04a1fe1b71acec732774ab388923171ce1fcc0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 167,
        "name": "Isaac Huang",
        "email": "he.huang@intel.com",
        "username": "isaac",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-06-07 00:00:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPlease ignore my comment above - I posted it at the wrong place.",
